'''MV ''Fairwind'' (MSL 251)''' was an Australian [[120ft Motor Lighter|Motor Stores Lighter]] wrecked off the [[New South Wales]] coast in 1950. MSL 251 and her sister ship, MSL 252 (later {{HMAS|Paluma|1945|6}}), were built by [[Tulloch Limited|Tulloch's Pty Ltd]] for the [[Australian Army]]. Completed in September 1946, the vessel was loaned to the Department of External Affairs and used for fishery surveys by the [[Papua and New Guinea Administration]]. The Department renamed the vessel MV ''Fairwind''.<ref name=fishrock>{{Cite web |last=Siviero |first=Damien |title=Wreck of the Fairwind found near South West Rocks |publisher=Fishrock.com |date= |url=http://fishrock.com.au/wreck-of-fairwind.html |accessdate=1 July 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100831022600/http://fishrock.com.au/wreck-of-fairwind.html |archivedate=31 August 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

==Loss==
In 1950, while on passage from [[Port Moresby]] to [[Sydney]], ''Fairwind'' disappeared off the mid-north coast of New South Wales during a [[cyclone]].<ref>{{Cite news |title=New search for ship |newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald |page=4 |date=30 June 1950 |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article18164429 |accessdate=1 July 2010}}</ref> She was last sighted near [[Smoky Cape]]. The ship's last communication was a radio report on 23 June, where she indicated that she was seeking shelter behind [[North Solitary Island]] short of fuel, but that she would attempt to reach [[Coffs Harbour]].<ref>{{Cite news |title="Fairwind" is presumed lost; 17 missing |newspaper=The Canberra Times |page=11 |date=29 June 1950 |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article2786305 |accessdate=30 June 2010}}</ref> Despite an extensive land and air search,<ref>{{Cite news |title=Missing Ship; Land, Air Search |newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald |page=3 |date=28 June 1950 |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article18168449 |accessdate=1 July 2010}}</ref> the crew of 17, including 12 [[Papuan peoples|Papuans]],<ref>{{Cite news |title=Pilot sees missing Navy ship |newspaper=The Argus |location=Melbourne |page=3 |date=28 June 1950 |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article22838668 |accessdate=1 July 2010}}</ref> were not found. It is official that all of the ''Fairwind'''s crew lost their lives in the sinking.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Hope Given Up For Crew Of Lost Ship |newspaper=The Sunday Herald |location=Sydney |page=4 |date=2 July 1950 |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article18483307 |accessdate=1 July 2010}}</ref>

==Rediscovery==
The fate of MV ''Fairwind'' was not positively established until August 2009, when her wreck was found in deep water off South West Rocks by a team of amateur divers.<ref name=fishrock/><ref>{{Cite web |last=Duffy |first=Connor |title=Divers solve maritime mystery |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Commission |date=30 June 2010 |url=http://www.abc.net.au/7.30/content/2010/s2941465.htm |accessdate=1 July 2010}}</ref> The wreck sits upright at a depth of {{convert|87|m}}. The wreck itself is mostly intact, with the forward and aft king posts projecting {{convert|15|m}} from the seabed.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Siviero |first=Damien |title=Discovering the Fairwind |publisher=Damien Siviero |date=30 June 2010 |url=http://damiensiviero.com/discovering-the-fairwind/ |accessdate=1 July 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101011082558/http://damiensiviero.com/discovering-the-fairwind/ |archivedate=11 October 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

