{{Notability|date=February 2011}}
'''Shannon Vyff''' (born June 10, 1975)<ref>[http://fora.humanityplus.org/index.php?/user/133-shannon-vyff/page__f__15 Humanity+ Profile]{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> is an American [[transhumanism|transhumanist]], [[cryonics|cryonicist]], and author. She is a director of both the Immortality Institute<ref>{{cite web | title=Immortality Institute Leadership| publisher=Immortality Institute |url=http://www.imminst.org/leadership | accessdate=2010-03-27}} </ref> and the Society for Venturism.<ref>{{cite web | last = Nye | first = James | title = Woman, 23, has her head frozen so she can be reborn after a cure for her brain cancer is found - against the wishes of her religious family | work = MailOnline | publisher = [[Daily Mail]] | date = January 24, 2013 | url = http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2268011/Kim-Suozzi-23-head-cryogenically-frozen-reborn-cure-brain-cancer-found.html | accessdate = 2013-01-28 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last = Dvorsky | first = George| title = 23-Year Old Kim Suozzi Undergoes Cryonic Preservation After Successful Fundraising Campaign
 | work = Futurism | publisher = [[Io9]]  | date = January 21, 2013 | url = http://io9.com/5977640/23+year-old-kim-suozzi-undergoes-cryonic-preservation-after-successful-fundraising-campaign | accessdate = 2013-01-28 }}</ref>

Vyff's approaches in promoting transhumanism and cryonics were given exposure when her essay "Confessions of a Proselytizing Immortalist" was published in 2006 as part of the book ''The Scientific Conquest of Death''. Vyff has also been interviewed by the media on subjects pertaining both to her approaches in promoting cryonics to the public at large (especially to children),<ref>{{cite web | title=Radio Interview with Dr. James J. Hughes| publisher=The Institute for Ethics and Emerging Technologies |url=http://ieet.org/index.php/IEET/IEETblog/2008/05/| accessdate=2010-03-21}}</ref> and her own motivations for becoming a cryonicist.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web | title=Freezing People into the Future: Uncover the Science Behind Cryonics| publisher=ABC News |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Health/video?id=4547826| accessdate=2010-03-27}}</ref>

Vyff published a science fiction adventure novel for children, ''21st Century Kids'', in 2007.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Perry |first1=Mike |year=2007 |title=21ST Century Kids |journal=Cryonics |publisher=Alcor Life Extension Foundation |volume=28 |issue=4 |pages=6 |url=http://www.alcor.org/cryonics/cryonics0704.pdf}}</ref>

She also is known for practicing [[caloric restriction]] for life extension purposes, and has been featured on multiple news stories regarding the prospect of life extension.<ref>[http://abcnews.go.com/2020/story?id=124351 Eating Less to Live Longer - ABC News<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[http://abcnews.go.com/Health/Longevity/story?id=4544003 Live to 150, Can You Do It? - ABC News<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[http://www.alcor.org/blog/update_abc_news_barbara_walter/ Update: ABC News & Barbara Walters Special - Alcor NewsAlcor News - News Blog of the Alcor Life Extension Foundation<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>

==Publications==

*{{cite book|title=21st Century Kids|last=Vyff|first=Shannon|publisher=Warren Publishing, Inc.|date=March 2007|pages=280|isbn=1-886057-00-1}} – [[science fiction]] adventure novel for children aged 9–12. The protagonists undergo [[cryonics|cryopreservation]] and are reanimated after 200 years. The book raises questions about the [[technological singularity]] and [[time travel]].
*{{cite book|title=The Scientific Conquest of Death: Essays on Infinite Lifespans|editor=Immortality Institute|publisher=Libros en Red|date=October 2004|pages=296|isbn=987-561-135-2}} - a collection of essays. Vyff is the author of the essay "Confessions of a Proselytizing Immortalist".<ref>[http://www.imminst.org/book#Vyff Book | Imminst.org - Immortality Institute<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[http://www.cbc-network.org/2006/11/book-review-the-scientific-conquest-of-death-essays-on-infinite-lifespans-ed-immortality-institute-buenos-aires-librosenred-2004-294-pages/ Book Review: The Scientific Conquest of Death: Essays on Infinite Lifespans, ed. Immortality Institute (Buenos Aires: LibrosEnRed, 2004), 294 pages<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>

==Personal life==
Vyff is a mother to four children, each of whom are signed up to cryonics.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> 
